			<A HREF="index.html">Writing UNIX Manual Pages</A> &#8211; <Q>Spell-checking Manpages</Q>
		</DIV>
		<DIV>
			<H1>SYNOPSIS</H1>
			<P>
				This tutorial illustrates how to check your manuals for spelling.
			</P>
		</DIV>
		<DIV>
			<H1>DESCRIPTION</H1>
			<P>
				It's unsurprising that most spell-checkers barf on <A CLASS="external"
				HREF="http://mdocml.bsd.lv/mdoc.7.html">mdoc</A> input, as it's difficult to parse text from control structures.
				The most convenient method is to use <A CLASS="external"
				HREF="http://www.lasr.cs.ucla.edu/geoff/ispell.html">ispell</A> or <A CLASS="external"
				HREF="http://aspell.net/">GNU aspell</A>.  Both have similar calling syntax.  For this example, let <SPAN
				CLASS="file">foo.1</SPAN> be the name of your manual.
			</P>
			<P CLASS="code">
				% ispell -n foo.1
			</P>
			<P CLASS="code">
				% aspell -n foo.1
			</P>
			<P>
				If these are not available and you have <SPAN CLASS="cmd">deroff</SPAN> installed, you can pipe its output
				directly into <SPAN CLASS="cmd">spell</SPAN>.  Both of these utilites are found on most reasonable UNIX
				installations.
			</P>
			<P CLASS="code">
				% deroff foo.1 | spell
			</P>
		</DIV>
